<h1>LG Washer Bearing Replacement Cost</h1>

<p>Replacing a worn drum bearing on an LG washer costs $320–420 in Los Angeles — it's one of the bigger jobs because the drum comes out and the tub often splits, but it's well under the price of a new machine and buys years of quiet operation. Here's what's in that price and what moves it. The $65 diagnostic is waived with the repair. Call (323) 990-7550.</p>

<h2>Cost Breakdown</h2>
<p>The bearing job breaks down into a modest part and a lot of labor. An OEM bearing-and-seal kit is the inexpensive piece; the bulk of the $320–420 is the work — tearing the machine down, pulling the drum, pressing out the old bearing, fitting the new one, and reassembling it correctly. That hands-on time is where the cost lives, and it's why a bearing sits at the higher end of common washer repairs.</p>

<h2>What Affects the Price</h2>
<p>Where your job lands in the $320–420 range depends mostly on the model. Some LG tubs split cleanly to reach the bearing; others take more disassembly, which adds labor. Front-load machines generally run a bit more than top-loaders because of how they come apart. We also check the condition of the tub seal and the spider arm while we're in there — if the spider is corroded it changes the picture, and we'll show you before going further.</p>

<h2>Repair vs Replace</h2>
<p>At $320–420, a bearing replacement is roughly a third of the $800–1,500 a comparable new LG washer costs delivered and installed, and it buys another eight to ten years on a machine you already know. That math favors the repair on an otherwise sound washer. If your machine is loud and walking across the floor, our guide to an <a href="/washer/symptoms/lg-washer-shaking/">LG washer shaking and banging</a> covers how we tell a worn bearing from a balance or suspension problem before any teardown.</p>

<h2>What's Included</h2>
<p>The price covers the OEM bearing and tub seal as a kit, all the labor to tear down and reassemble the machine, and a one-year warranty on parts and labor. The $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair, and we confirm the bearing is the real cause before quoting so you're not paying for a teardown you don't need.</p>

<p>Hearing a grinding rumble on spin? Our LG Dryer Repair techs handle bearing replacements across LA, Orange County, and Ventura County — we confirm the cause on-site and quote before any work. Call (323) 990-7550; the $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer Bearing Replacement Cost</h2>

<h3>How much does LG washer bearing replacement cost?</h3>
<p>LG washer bearing replacement costs $320–420 installed in Los Angeles, including an OEM bearing and seal kit. Most of that is labor — the drum has to come out and the tub often splits to reach the bearing. The $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair.</p>

<h3>Why is bearing replacement one of the pricier LG washer repairs?</h3>
<p>Because it's labor-heavy — reaching the bearing means pulling the drum and, on many LG models, splitting the outer tub, a 2–3 hour job. The bearing and seal parts are modest; the cost is the teardown and reassembly done right.</p>

<h3>Does the price include the seal too?</h3>
<p>Yes — we replace the tub seal with the bearing as a kit, and that's included in the $320–420. Doing the bearing without the seal just causes another failure, so we never split them. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Is a $320–420 bearing job worth it versus a new washer?</h3>
<p>Usually yes — a comparable new LG washer is $800–1,500, so a bearing replacement is a fraction of that and buys another 8–10 years. We'll give you an honest read if other major parts are also worn.</p>

<h3>How do I know the noise is the bearing and not something else?</h3>
<p>A worn bearing makes a loud grinding rumble that worsens on spin, often with drum play you can feel by hand. We confirm it on-site before quoting — a similar noise can come from the drive system, and we don't charge you for a bearing if that's not what's failing.</p>

